metadata.name: Neural Collapse #353
metadata.description:
What happens when your brain overloads, or when you lose control of your giant robot.

A study on the repetition and stacking of a simple but very dynamic structure.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.
You can find more informations on the piece, its design and origins, here: https://ulucode.com/wp/neural-collapse/

Interactivity : 
- You can hover your mouse on the connectors to close them... temporarily
- Press and hold the mouse button to slightly move the viewpoint.

- Press "a" to increase quality of the antialiasing (3 levels), at the cost of performances. Especially useful on the palettes using outlines.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels. I recommend starting with "4".

GPU recommended. Best performances on Chrome in general.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Chaos Culture #220
metadata.description:
"Chaos Culture" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

„ÄäË•øÈÅäË®ò„ÄãÁ¨¨‰∏ÄÂõû:„ÄåÊ∑∑Ê≤åÊú™ÂàÜÂ§©Âú∞‰∫ÇÔºåËå´Ëå´Ê∏∫Ê∏∫ÁÑ°‰∫∫Ë¶ã„ÄÇ„Äç

Chaos Culture is the final chapter of this series. There is a legend in the East that before Pan Gu opened up the sky and created the earth, the world was a chaotic place, and no one knew its appearance. And I have always been fascinated by this mythical story since he was a child.

These three works have a father-son relationship, Research > Memory > Culture, with each work re-growing through the remnants of the previous work, depending on its image. From the beginning of the creative coding, I like the concept of recursion the most. Here I experiment with my central thinking through this iterative relationship so that the work is not only the shadow of the artist but also the pulling force of repetition.

"Ê∑∑Ê≤å" Chaos in Eastern culture represents the initial state of things. This state is consistent with what we believe in generative art: Anything can happen if different forces are applied. Letting chaos grow out of order and then destroying it, the iterative process, is like my usual dialogue with myself, and maybe it's all just a diary.

Through these three series of works, whether I can eventually find everything in my childhood fantasy, I am not sure yet. The only thing I can be sure of is that I will continue to explore.

- Click the mouse to save an artwork.
- Collectors who own this NFT have the right to print the work.

Artist: Aluan Wang (ileivoivm).
Made with p5js and glsl.

metadata.name: Ancient Trees II. Close ups #15
metadata.description:
This work continues the exploration of Ancient Trees I, playing with variations on the characteristics of a pair of related trees.

In addition to the branch parameters, Ancient Trees II introduces new constants governing  leaf morphology and color.

Try resizing the browser window to experiment with different aspect ratios. 

Press "2" To "4" to increase the resolution
Press "S" to download a PNG file.

Built with p5js.

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #291
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. ‚ÄúThe Bugged Tree‚Äù‚Äôs code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren‚Äôt under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there‚Äôs a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Pastoral Palettes #133
metadata.description:
Pastoral Palettes showcases 93 beautiful hand tuned palettes in a generative pastoral setting. The palettes themselves pay homage to great paintings from the past up to the present. Isolating the palettes in this way brings out the artistic genius of the underlying artwork in a unique way. The palette name in the features contains the painting and artist.

The algorithmic parts of Pastoral Palettes use many techniques to create the scene and generate the ground, sky, trees, and shrubbery. Using random perlin noise for the placement ensures a more natural looking scene. The sky is a gradient composed from the palette. Each blade of grass is drawn individually using perlin noise to create the color pattern in the grass. Each tree and shrub is randomly constructed and colored using color blending in the transition colors. The grass generation is the most computationally expensive and the density can be adjusted with the arrow keys, see below.

The mint size is relatively small in relation to the number of palettes, so to ensure that all palettes get generated at least once, we are including 2 palettes for each mint.

Each mint of Pastoral Palettes comes with sunlight and moonlight views, toggled with the 'f' key. The palettes look strikingly different for each view - you can choose which one you like best.

Variations:

 - Each palette has an equal chance of being minted. Since the mint size is so small compared to the number of palettes, there is a high chance of getting a rare palette. 
 - 2% chance of getting 5 palettes instead of the default of 2. 
 - 10% chance of getting a sun/moon in the sky.
 - Each layout will be entirely unique.

Pastoral Palettes is responsive and looks great on any size display. They look especially good on large displays of 2K, 4K, and even 8K.

'f' flips between sunlight and moonlight views.
'p' cycles through the palettes.
's' saves an image in the exact size of the current display.
'up/down arrow' adjusts the grass density. Denser grass may look better at some resolutions, but takes considerably longer to render, particularly on large displays.

metadata.name: Assemble #173
metadata.description:
Assemble is a 2D shape composition with a procedural background texture.

There are two types of shapes, squares and blobs, composed in a grid.

12 color palettes, procedurally generated using a GAN algorithm.

Available in [1:1] and [3:4] resolutions.

--------------------------------------------------

Keys [1-4]

1 - Variation (maintaining resolution)
2 - Variation (changing resolution)
3 - Change color (only in [3:4] resolution)
4 - Save canvas (Live View)

--------------------------------------------------

Made with p5.

-dePaula

metadata.name: The Voyage #14
metadata.description:
The more we explore, the more things we realize there are to be explored. The more questions we find answers to, the more answers we find that require the right questions to be asked.

What is there beyond the edge of knowledge; what was, when things were none?

Will it be our body or our mind to discover that first?

And so The Voyage begins...

* * *

Press R to hide/show cosmic rain (takes a few seconds).
Press S to save as PNG.

metadata.name: Connected City #11
metadata.description:
A cityscape in a far away world that is lost in space where digital life is to be found either: gone, alive or desert. 

Huge antennas capture space communications defining time and life habits of the population.

Variations include 5 palettes, disposition of buildings, sky and the city lights backdrop. 

Three modes with light, dark and the rare gold one.

- hit 's' for saving a 4096 x 2304 .png file for personal use
